This short canticum in anapaestic octonarii is free from the vague- ness of thought which character- izes some of the more elaborate cantica. It is a good specimen of the cantica in a single meter, like Bacch. 385 ff. ; 925 ff„ and ex- hibits in a rather marked degree

the distinctive features of the half- lyrical popular verse, the asynde-ta (spurcificurm inmanem, intole- randum, uesanum; frangere, ruere„ scindere), the alliterations (laetus lubens laudes3 grates gratias; pauperibus parcere; diuites damnare atque domare, mendicis modesti; pax propi- tia), the fulness of expression (821 ; omnia item una mecum, 8343 quasi . . . haud secus. 835). These lines deserve careful atten- tion. There is scarcely a character- istic of the style of Plautus except the idioms proper to dialogue, which is not illustrated here.
